        <p>Museum of Modern Art<lb/>11 West 53<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> Street<lb/>Ci
            5-8900<lb/><placeName key="49021" type="write">New York</placeName> 19, <placeName
            key="50589">N.Y.</placeName></p>

        <p rend="right"><date when="1947-06-08" cert="high">June 8, 1947</date></p>

        <p><emph n="salutation">Dear Mr. <persName key="73655" role="rec"
          >Schocken</persName></emph>:</p>

        <p>Last week, I repeatedly called up at your office to make an appointment with you. Your
            secretary<note type="reg"><persName key="x"/></note>, obviously after having spoken with
          you, suggested that I should write to you about the purpose of the interview I
          desired.</p>

        <p>There must be a misunderstanding. I have nothing specific up my sleeves, except the great
          pleasure of having a talk with you, which of course might touch on personal plans and
          literary projects. Also, before your departure last year you had told me over the wire
          that you looked forward to seeing me after your return.</p>

        <p>Since you are no doubt frightfully crowded on the rare occasions you are coming to town,
          I naturally understand that you may have no time for me. But should you nevertheless be
          able to cut out an hour for lunch or so, you would make me really happy.</p>

        <p rend="center"><emph n="salute">With my best wishes,<lb/>Sincerely yours</emph>,</p>

        <p rend="center"><persName key="7721" role="aut">Siegfried Kracauer</persName></p>

        <p rend="center">My book "From Caligari to Hitler" has been published at the end of April.
          Things do not look too bad: there will be a reprinting in July.</p>

      </div>
